            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">A Unix timestamp (also called Epoch time or Unix Epoch time) is the number of seconds (or milliseconds) that have elapsed since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC, not counting leap seconds. It is the standard way computers represent time.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 bg-canvas">
          <button type="button" class="faq-toggle w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>What's the difference between Unix timestamp in seconds and milliseconds?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">Unix timestamps can be expressed in seconds (10 digits, e.g., 1710000000) or milliseconds (13 digits, e.g., 1710000000000). JavaScript Date uses milliseconds. Many APIs use seconds. This tool handles both automatically.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 bg-canvas">
          <button type="button" class="faq-toggle w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>What is the Year 2038 problem?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">32-bit signed integers max out at 2,147,483,647 seconds, which is January 19, 2038, 03:14:07 UTC. Systems using 32-bit signed time_t will overflow after this date. Modern 64-bit systems don't have this problem.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 bg-canvas">
          <button type="button" class="faq-toggle w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>How do I convert a timestamp to a human-readable date?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">Multiply seconds by 1000 to get milliseconds, then use Date constructor: new Date(timestamp * 1000). The Date object provides methods to format the date in any timezone, including ISO strings, locale strings, and custom formats.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ring-1 ring-inset ring-hairline rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-lvl2 bg-canvas">
          <button type="button" class="faq-toggle w-full px-6 py-4 flex items-center justify-between text-left font-sans text-sm font-bold text-ink hover:bg-canvas-soft-2 transition-colors cursor-pointer" aria-expanded="false">
            <span>Can timestamps represent future dates?</span>
            <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-mute transition-transform duration-200 flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden border-t border-hairline px-6 py-4 bg-canvas-soft">
            <p class="text-body text-sm font-sans leading-relaxed">Yes. Unix timestamps can represent any date from 1970 to approximately year 292,277,026,596 for 64-bit systems. Future timestamps are commonly used for scheduling, token expiration (like JWTs), and countdown timers.</p>
